## Commits (Conventional Commits)

- Use **Conventional Commits**: `type(scope): subject`
- **Subject**:
  - Imperative mood, sentence case, **no period** at the end
  - Max **~72 characters** in the first line
- **Body** (optional):
  - Wrap at **~72** chars
  - Explain *why* and *what changed* at a high level; avoid restating the diff
- **Footer** (optional):
  - `Fixes #123` / `Closes #123` when applicable

## Allowed `type` values (prefer these)

- `feat`: new user-facing behavior (new widget API, new variant, new effect, example screen)
- `fix`: bug fix
- `docs`: documentation-only changes
- `refactor`: behavior-preserving restructure
- `test`: tests only
- `chore`: repo hygiene (formatting, tooling), non-user-facing
- `ci`: CI-only changes
- `revert`: revert commits (use `revert: ...`)

## `scope` (use one; keep small)

- `button`, `style`, `effects`, `example`, `docs`, `pub`, `a11y`, `theme`

## Examples (good)

- `feat(effects): add glow effect compositor`
- `fix(button): prevent press while loading`
- `docs(phase-2): document segmented control showcase`
- `chore: enable stricter lints in analysis_options`
- `revert: feat(effects): add glow effect compositor`

## Examples (avoid)

- `update stuff` (no type/scope; vague)
- `WIP` / `asdf` (not descriptive)
- Huge unrelated changes bundled into one commit (split when possible)

## Branches (recommended)

- `feat/<short-topic>`
- `fix/<issue-or-topic>`
- `doc/<topic>`
- `chore/<topic>`

## PR / commit hygiene

- Prefer **one logical change per commit** (easy to review and bisect)
- If you touch public API, update:
  - `CHANGELOG.md` (when releases are being prepared)
  - `doc/PHASE_*` if behavior/taxonomy changes
